            <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mi>i</mi>
              <mo>=</mo>
              <mn>1</mn>
            </mrow>
            <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mi>n</mi>
            </mrow>
          </munderover>
          <mi>p</mi>
          <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
          <msub>
            <mi>f</mi>
            <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mi>i</mi>
            </mrow>
          </msub>
          <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
          <mi>log</mi>
          <mo>&#x2061;<!-- ⁡ --></mo>
          <mi>p</mi>
          <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
          <msub>
            <mi>f</mi>
            <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mi>i</mi>
            </mrow>
          </msub>
          <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
        </mstyle>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \textstyle \sum _{i=1}^{n}p(f_{i})\log p(f_{i})}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/c174765a660758c7574652c26d0f28a362868190" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -1.005ex; width:19.322ex; height:3.176ex;" alt="{\displaystyle \textstyle \sum _{i=1}^{n}p(f_{i})\log p(f_{i})}"/></span>, represents the cost (in bits) of optimally encoding (or transmitting) feature information when no category information is available.  The value of the <i>category utility</i> will, in the above formulation, be negative (???).
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Category_Utility_and_Mutual_Information">Category Utility and Mutual Information</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Category_utility&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Category Utility and Mutual Information">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>It is mentioned in <a href="#CITEREFGluckCorter1985">Gluck &amp; Corter (1985)</a> and <a href="#CITEREFCorterGluck1992">Corter &amp; Gluck (1992)</a> that the category utility is equivalent to the <a href="/wiki/Mutual_information" title="Mutual information">mutual information</a>.  Here we provide a simple demonstration of the nature of this equivalence.  Let us assume a set of entities each having the same <span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle n}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <mi>n</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle n}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/a601995d55609f2d9f5e233e36fbe9ea26011b3b" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -0.338ex; width:1.395ex; height:1.676ex;" alt="n"/></span>  features, i.e.,  feature set <span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle F=\{f_{i}\},\ i=1\ldots n}">
